NVDI in Gaza

About Geovisualisations Technical Reports Python & Friends CV Contact

Gaza has seen massive amounts of destruction since the Hamas led attack on Israel on the 7th of October 2023.
This is an attempt to use NVDI to map damage from the conflict.

These maps show the NVDI of Gaza in the summers of 2023 and 2024, and how vast areas of green infrastructure have been lost, particularly in the south of Gaza City.
The histograms show that in 2023, there were three peaks on the chart, but the peak at 0.2 has been flattened by 2024. The chart becomes more skewed to the right, and the mode value (approximately 0.1) and the negative values becomes more frequent.

Methodology

The basic methodology used is straightforward; a raster of the NVDI of Gaza was calculated in Google Earth Engine for the summers of 2023 and 2024, and then the difference between them was calculated to show how much vegetation had been lost in that time.

The code used to calculate the NVDI is below, and can be viewed in GEE here: https://code.earthengine.google.com/271bcf77d0a44ddb40dd8296a6806d8a

var gaza=table2; //import shapefile
var gazabound=geometry2; //import geometry object to set bounds

function nvdi(start,end,shapefile,bound){
  
var sat1= imageCollection.filterBounds(shapefile) // fetch Sentinel image and clip to bounds of shapefile
.filter(ee.Filter.lte('CLOUDY_PIXEL_PERCENTAGE',10))  //only use images with <10% clouds
.filterDate(start,end); //set time constraint for imagery

var visParams_RGB = {bands: ['B4', 'B3', 'B2'], max: 3048}; //set bands to true colour image
var med1 = sat1.reduce(ee.Reducer.median()); //calculate median over a small area to reduce resolution
var clip1=med1.clip(bound); //clip to bounds of shapefile
var visParams_median = {bands:['B4_median', 'B3_median', 'B2_median'], max: 3048}; 
var nvdi1 = clip1.normalizedDifference(['B8_median','B4_median']); //calculate NVDI
var visParams_ndvi = {min: -0.2, max: 0.8, palette: 'FFFFFF, CE7E45, DF923D, F1B555, FCD163, 99B718, 74A901, 66A000, 529400, 3E8601, 207401, 056201, 004C00, 023B01, 012E01, 011D01, 011301'}; //style NVDI image
Map.addLayer(nvdi1,visParams_ndvi,'NDVI '+start); //show NVDI image on map
Export.image.toDrive({image: nvdi1,  scale:10,  maxPixels:10e12,}); //export image to Google Drive
}

nvdi("2023-06-01","2023-08-31",gaza,gazabound) //produce before image
nvdi("2024-06-01","2024-08-31",gaza,gazabound) //produce after image

This approach to mapping the destruction from conflict works particularly well for Gaza for a number of reasons:

  • Most of the vegetation in Gaza is composed of scattered trees in a very dense urban environment. Because almost all the vegetation is part of the built environment, its loss can be considered a proxy for damage to the built environment. This makes this methodology unsuitable for use in areas with large amounts of natural vegetation or fields, like the east of Ukraine, for example.
  • The conflict has also gone on for more than a year, which means that imagery from the same season can be compared in different years. This methodology cannot be used for Israel's October 2024 incursion in southern Lebanon at present, because two different seasons would be being compared.
  • Gaza has seen massive conflict over a relatively small area (under 400km) compared to other warzones, which lessens the computing power required and makes the visualisations easier to interpret.

Implications

The NVDI has been used here as a proxy for damage to the built environment, but it is also important to consider the loss of NVDI as a problem in its own right. Holail et al. (2024) report that the amount of farmland (of which there is a small amount in Gaza) has reduced by 34% since the start of the conflict, which has implications for food security. The loss of vegetation will also impact the ecology of the region.

Comparing these results to the maps from a BBC investigation shows that the areas with large amounts of vegetation loss do match up strongly with those identified as being damaged by other means.
